node.text:
Exploring one of Buenos Aires most iconic neighbourhoods 🇦🇷

La Boca was originally the first Buenos Aires harbor. It was called that way in reference to the Riachuelo, which would empty into the Río de la Plata in the shape of a big mouth, “la boca” means the mouth in Spanish.

The neighborhood was settled and built by Italian immigrants that worked in the warehouses and meatpacking plants in the area. They constructed their houses out of materials found in the shipyards and painted with the same paint used for the ships.

Definitely and a must when visiting Buenos Aires, this neighborhood is full of color history and tango.

Buenos Aires 🇦🇷 
"Even though you find yourself in a city of nearly 13 million inhabitants, you have a feeling of being at home. It's as if the city opens its arms and says: 'This is me; come explore.'"
••
Spending some weeks in the city where I lived most of the time growing up and i can’t be happier, i missed you Buenos Aires, is always nice to be back home.

node.text:
Hierapolis-Pamukkale 📍
•
Hierapolis was an ancient Greek city, located on the top of modern Pamukkale and is an outstanding World Heritage site. 

Is believed to have been founded by Eumenies II, the King of Pergamum, in the 2nd century BC.

After exploring the hot springs walking about the ruins of the baths, temples and other Greek monuments is a a great plan, i walked around for 2 hours and saw some stunning ruins.

My favorite sight was roman amphitheatre. 🎭

node.text:
Pamukkale means Cotton Castle in Turkish, and it is true that it looks like one 🤍
•
This is one of the most beautiful natural wonder i have ever seen, this magical place is located in the southwestern Turkish province of Denizli. 

The hot springs here are formed of terraced pools created by pure white travertine creating this beautiful natural landscape. 

To be honest pictures can’t show the real beauty of this stunning place.
